# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kivy-framework
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:kivy-framework/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] In computer science, **declarative programming** is a programming paradigm that expresses the logic of a computation without fully describing its control flow.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] This is in contrast with imperative programming, which implements algorithms in explicit steps.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Declarative programming may consider programs as theories of a formal logic, and computations as deductions in that logical theory.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Declarative programming at times simplifies the writing of parallel programs.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Common declarative language paradigms include logic programming (e.g., Prolog, Datalog, answer set programming), and algebraic modeling systems.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is often defined as any style of programming that is not imperative.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] A number of other common definitions attempt to define it by simply contrasting it with imperative programming.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] These definitions overlap substantially.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is a non-imperative style of programming in which programs describe their desired results without explicitly listing commands or steps that must be performed.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages are characterized by a mostly declarative programming style.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] In logic programming, programs consist of sentences expressed in logical form, and computation uses those sentences to solve problems, which are also expressed in logical form.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] In a pure functional language, such as Haskell, all functions are without side effects, and state changes are only represented as functions that transform the state, which is explicitly represented as a first-class object in the program.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Although pure functional languages are non-imperative, they often provide a facility for describing the effect of a function as a series of steps.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Other functional languages, such as Lisp, OCaml and Erlang, support a mixture of procedural and functional programming.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Some logic programming languages, such as Prolog, and database query languages, such as SQL, while declarative in principle, also support a procedural style of programming.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is an umbrella term that includes a number of better-known programming paradigms.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Constraint programming states relations between variables in the form of constraints that specify the properties of the target solution.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] The set of constraints is solved by giving a value to each variable so that the solution is consistent with the maximum number of constraints.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Constraint programming often complements other paradigms: functional, logical, or even imperative programming.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Makefiles, for example, specify dependencies in a declarative fashion, but include an imperative list of actions to take as well.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Similarly, yacc specifies a context free grammar declaratively, but includes code snippets from a host language, which is usually imperative (such as C).
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages, such as Prolog, Datalog and answer set programming, compute by proving that a goal is a logical consequence of the program, or by showing that the goal is true in a model defined by the program.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Prolog computes by reducing goals to subgoals, top-down using backward reasoning, whereas most Datalog systems compute bottom-up using forward reasoning.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Answer set programs typically use SAT solvers to generate a model of the program.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Models, or mathematical representations, of physical systems may be implemented in computer code that is declarative.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] The code contains a number of equations, not imperative assignments, that describe ("declare") the behavioral relationships.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] When a model is expressed in this formalism, a computer is able to perform algebraic manipulations to best formulate the solution algorithm.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] The mathematical causality is typically imposed at the boundaries of the physical system, while the behavioral description of the system itself is declarative or acausal.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Declarative modeling languages and environments include Analytica, Modelica and Simile.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Prolog (1972) stands for "PROgramming in LOGic." It was developed for natural language question answering, using SL resolution both to deduce answers to queries and to parse and generate natural language sentences.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] The building blocks of a Prolog program are *facts* and *rules*.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Given this program, the query `eat(tom,jerry)` succeeds, while `eat(jerry,tom)` fails.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Moreover, the query `eat(X,jerry)` succeeds with the answer substitution `X=tom`.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Prolog executes programs top-down, using SLD resolution to reason backwards, reducing goals to subgoals.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] In this example, it uses the last rule of the program to reduce the goal of answering the query `eat(X,jerry)` to the subgoals of first finding an X such that `big(X)` holds and then of showing that `small(jerry)` holds.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] It repeatedly uses rules to further reduce subgoals to other subgoals, until it eventually succeeds in unifying all subgoals with facts in the program.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] This backward reasoning, goal-reduction strategy treats rules in logic programs as procedures, and makes Prolog both a declarative and procedural programming language.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] The broad range of Prolog applications is highlighted in the Year of Prolog Book, celebrating the 50 year anniversary of Prolog.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] The origins of Datalog date back to the beginning of logic programming, but it was identified as a separate area around 1977.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Syntactically and semantically, it is a subset of Prolog.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] But because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Most Datalog systems execute programs bottom-up, using rules to reason forwards, deriving new facts from existing facts, and terminating when there are no new facts that can be derived, or when the derived facts unify with the query.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Datalog has been applied to such problems as data integration, information extraction, networking, security, cloud computing and machine learning.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Answer set programming (ASP) evolved in the late 1990s, based on the stable model (answer set) semantics of logic programming.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Like Datalog, it is a subset of Prolog; and, because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Most implementations of ASP execute a program by first *grounding* the program, replacing all variables in rules by constants in all possible ways, and then using a propositional SAT solver, such as the DPLL algorithm to generate one or more models of the program.
[src:kivy-framework/declarative-programming] Its applications are oriented towards solving difficult search problems and knowledge representation.
[src:kivy-framework/kivy-framework] Kivy is the main framework developed by the Kivy organization, alongside Python for Android, Kivy for iOS, and several other libraries meant to be used on all platforms.
[src:kivy-framework/kivy-framework] In 2012, Kivy got a $5000 grant from the Python Software Foundation for porting it to Python 3.3.
[src:kivy-framework/kivy-framework] Kivy also supports the Raspberry Pi which was funded through Bountysource.
[src:kivy-framework/kivy-framework] Kivy is an evolution of the PyMT project.
[src:kivy-framework/kivy-framework] The Kv language is a language dedicated to describing user interface and interactions in Kivy framework.
[src:kivy-framework/kivy-framework] As with other user interface markup languages, it is possible to easily create a whole UI and attach interaction.
[src:kivy-framework/kivy-framework] For example, to create a Loading dialog that includes a file browser, and a Cancel / Load button, one could first create the base widget in Python and then construct the UI in Kv.
[src:kivy-framework/kivy-framework] Alternatively, the layout (here, Box Layout) and the buttons can be loaded directly in the main.py file.
[src:kivy-framework/kivy-framework] Kivy participated in Google Summer of Code under the Python Software Foundation.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In computing, **multi-touch** is technology that enables a surface (a touchpad or touchscreen) to recognize the presence of more than one point of contact with the surface at the same time.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] The origins of multitouch began at CERN, MIT, University of Toronto, Carnegie Mellon University and Bell Labs in the 1970s.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] CERN started using multi-touch screens as early as 1976 for the controls of the Super Proton Synchrotron.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Capacitive multi-touch displays were popularized by Apple's iPhone in 2007.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Multi-touch may be used to implement additional functionality, such as pinch to zoom or to activate certain subroutines attached to predefined gestures using gesture recognition.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Several uses of the term multi-touch resulted from the quick developments in this field, with several companies using the term to market older technology called *gesture-enhanced single-touch* or several other terms by other companies and researchers.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Several other similar or related terms attempt to differentiate between whether a device can exactly determine or only approximate the location of different points of contact to further differentiate between the various technological capabilities, but they are often used as synonyms in marketing.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Multi-touch is commonly implemented using capacitive sensing technology in mobile devices and smart devices.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] A capacitive touchscreen typically consists of a capacitive touch sensor, application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) controller and digital signal processor (DSP) fabricated from CMOS (complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor) technology.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] A more recent alternative approach is optical touch technology, based on image sensor technology.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In computing, multi-touch is technology that enables a touchpad or touchscreen to recognize more than one or more than two points of contact with the surface.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Apple popularized the term "multi-touch" in 2007 with which it implemented additional functionality, such as pinch to zoom or to activate certain subroutines attached to predefined gestures.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] The two different uses of the term resulted from the quick developments in this field, with several companies using the term to market older technology called *gesture-enhanced single-touch* or several other terms by other companies and researchers.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] The use of touchscreen technology predates both multi-touch technology and the personal computer.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Early synthesizer and electronic instrument builders like Hugh Le Caine and Robert Moog experimented with using touch-sensitive capacitance sensors to control the sounds made by their instruments.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] IBM began building the first touch screens in the late 1960s.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In 1972, Control Data released the PLATO IV computer, an infrared terminal used for educational purposes, which employed single-touch points in a 16×16 array user interface.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] These early touchscreens only registered one point of touch at a time.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] On-screen keyboards (a well-known feature today) were thus awkward to use, because key-rollover and holding down a shift key while typing another were not possible.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In 1976 a new x-y capacitive screen, based on the capacitance touch screens developed in 1972 by Danish electronics engineer Bent Stumpe, was developed at CERN.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] This technology, allowing an exact location of the different touch points, was used to develop a new type of human machine interface (HMI) for the control room of the Super Proton Synchrotron particle accelerator.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In a handwritten note dated 11 March 1972, Stumpe presented his proposed solution – a capacitive touch screen with a fixed number of programmable buttons presented on a display.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] The screen was to consist of a set of capacitors etched into a film of copper on a sheet of glass, each capacitor being constructed so that a nearby flat conductor, such as the surface of a finger, would increase the capacitance by a significant amount.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] The capacitors were to consist of fine lines etched in copper on a sheet of glass – fine enough (80 μm) and sufficiently far apart (80 μm) to be invisible.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In the final device, a simple lacquer coating prevented the fingers from actually touching the capacitors.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In the same year, MIT described a keyboard with variable graphics capable of multi-touch detection.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In the early 1980s, The University of Toronto's Input Research Group were among the earliest to explore the software side of multi-touch input systems.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] A 1982 system at the University of Toronto used a frosted-glass panel with a camera placed behind the glass.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] When a finger or several fingers pressed on the glass, the camera would detect the action as one or more black spots on an otherwise white background, allowing it to be registered as an input.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Since the size of a dot was dependent on pressure (how hard the person was pressing on the glass), the system was somewhat pressure-sensitive as well.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Of note, this system was input only and not able to display graphics.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In 1983, Bell Labs at Murray Hill published a comprehensive discussion of touch-screen based interfaces, though it makes no mention of multiple fingers.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In the same year, the video-based Video Place/Video Desk system of Myron Krueger was influential in development of multi-touch gestures such as pinch-to-zoom, though this system had no touch interaction itself.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] By 1984, both Bell Labs and Carnegie Mellon University had working multi-touch-screen prototypes – both input and graphics – that could respond interactively in response to multiple finger inputs.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] The Bell Labs system was based on capacitive coupling of fingers, whereas the CMU system was optical.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In 1985, the canonical multitouch pinch-to-zoom gesture was demonstrated, with coordinated graphics, on CMU's system.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In October 1985, Steve Jobs signed a non-disclosure agreement to tour CMU's Sensor Frame multi-touch lab.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In 1991, Pierre Wellner advanced the topic publishing about his multi-touch "Digital Desk", which supported multi-finger and pinching motions.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Various companies expanded upon these inventions in the beginning of the twenty-first century.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Between 1999 and 2005, the company Fingerworks developed various multi-touch technologies, including Touchstream keyboards and the iGesture Pad. in the early 2000s Alan Hedge, professor of human factors and ergonomics at Cornell University published several studies about this technology.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In 2005, Apple acquired Fingerworks and its multi-touch technology.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In 2001, Microsoft's table-top touch platform, Microsoft PixelSense (formerly Surface) started development, which interacts with both the user's touch and their electronic devices and became commercial on May 29, 2007.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Similarly, in 2001, Mitsubishi Electric Research Laboratories (MERL) began development of a multi-touch, multi-user system called DiamondTouch.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In 2004, French start-up JazzMutant developed the Lemur Input Device, a music controller that became in 2005 the first commercial product to feature a proprietary transparent multi-touch screen, allowing direct, ten-finger manipulation on the display.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In January 2007, multi-touch technology became mainstream with the iPhone, and in its iPhone announcement Apple even stated it "invented multi touch".
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Nonetheless, both the function and the term predate the announcement or patent requests, except for the area of capacitive mobile screens, which did not exist before Fingerworks/Apple's technology (Fingerworks filed patents in 2001–2005, subsequent multi-touch refinements were patented by Apple).
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Patent and Trademark office declared that the "pinch-to-zoom" functionality was predicted by U.S.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Patent # 7,844,915 relating to gestures on touch screens, filed by Bran Ferren and Daniel Hillis in 2005, as was inertial scrolling, thus invalidated a key claims of Apple's patent.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In 2008, the Diamondtouch became a commercial product and is also based on capacitance, but able to differentiate between multiple simultaneous users or rather, the chairs in which each user is seated or the floorpad on which the user is standing.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In 2007, NORTD labs open source system offered its CUBIT (multi-touch).
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In 2009, Android 2.0 has added support for multi-touch.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Also, in 2009, Windows 7 and Windows Mobile 6.5 has added support for multi-touch.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Small-scale touch devices rapidly became commonplace in 2008.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] The number of touch screen telephones was expected to increase from 200,000 shipped in 2006 to 21 million in 2012.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In May 2015, Apple was granted a patent for a "fusion keyboard", which turns individual physical keys into multi-touch buttons.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Apple has retailed and distributed numerous products using multi-touch technology, most prominently including its iPhone smartphone and iPad tablet.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Additionally, Apple also holds several patents related to the implementation of multi-touch in user interfaces, but the legitimacy of some patents has been disputed.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Apple additionally attempted to register "Multi-touch" as a trademark in the United States—its request was denied by the United States Patent and Trademark Office because it considered the term generic.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Multi-touch sensing and processing occurs via an ASIC sensor that is attached to the touch surface.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Usually, separate companies make the ASIC and screen that combine into a touch screen; conversely, a touchpad's surface and ASIC are usually manufactured by the same company.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] There have been large companies in recent years that have expanded into the growing multi-touch industry, with systems designed for everything from the casual user to multinational organizations.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] It is now common for laptop manufacturers to include multi-touch touchpads on their laptops, and tablet computers respond to touch input rather than traditional stylus input and it is supported by many recent operating systems.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] A few companies are focusing on large-scale surface computing rather than personal electronics, either large multi-touch tables or wall surfaces.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] These systems are generally used by government organizations, museums, and companies as a means of information or exhibit display.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Multi-touch has been implemented in several different ways, depending on the size and type of interface.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] The most popular form are mobile devices, tablets, touchtables and walls.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Both touchtables and touch walls project an image through acrylic or glass, and then back-light the image with LEDs.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Touch surfaces can also be made pressure-sensitive by the addition of a pressure-sensitive coating that flexes differently depending on how firmly it is pressed, altering the reflection.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Handheld technologies use a panel that carries an electrical charge.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] When a finger touches the screen, the touch disrupts the panel's electrical field.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] The disruption is registered as a computer event (gesture) and may be sent to the software, which may then initiate a response to the gesture event.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In the past few years, several companies have released products that use multi-touch.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In an attempt to make the expensive technology more accessible, hobbyists have also published methods of constructing DIY touchscreens.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Optical touch technology is based on image sensor technology.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] It functions when a finger or an object touches the surface, causing the light to scatter, the reflection of which is caught with sensors or cameras that send the data to software that dictates response to the touch, depending on the type of reflection measured.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Multi-touch touchscreen gestures enable predefined motions to interact with the device and software.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] An increasing number of devices like smartphones, tablet computers, laptops or desktop computers have functions that are triggered by multi-touch gestures.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Years before it was a viable consumer product, popular culture portrayed potential uses of multi-touch technology in the future, including in several installments of the *Star Trek* franchise.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In the 1982 Disney sci-fi film *Tron*, a device similar to the Microsoft Surface was shown.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] It took up an executive's entire desk and was used to communicate with the Master Control computer.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In the 2002 film *Minority Report*, Tom Cruise uses a set of gloves that resemble a multi-touch interface to browse through information.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In the 2005 film *The Island*, another form of a multi-touch computer was seen where the professor, played by Sean Bean, has a multi-touch desktop to organize files, based on an early version of Microsoft Surface (not be confused with the tablet computers that now bear that name).
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In 2007, the television series *CSI: Miami* introduced both surface and wall multi-touch displays in its sixth season.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Multi-touch technology can be seen in the 2008 James Bond film *Quantum of Solace*, where MI6 uses a touch interface to browse information about the criminal Dominic Greene.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In the 2008 film *The Day the Earth Stood Still*, Microsoft's Surface was used.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] The television series *NCIS: Los Angeles*, which premiered 2009, makes use of multi-touch surfaces and wall panels as an initiative to go digital.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In a 2008, an episode of the television series *The Simpsons*, Lisa Simpson travels to the underwater headquarters of Mapple to visit Steve Mobbs, who is shown to be performing multiple multi-touch hand gestures on a large touch wall.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] In the 2009, the film *District 9* the interface used to control the alien ship features similar technology.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] 10/GUI is a proposed new user interface paradigm.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Clayton Miller, it combines multi-touch input with a new windowing manager.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] It splits the touch surface away from the screen, so that user fatigue is reduced and the users' hands don't obstruct the display.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] Instead of placing windows all over the screen, the windowing manager, Con10uum, uses a linear paradigm, with multi-touch used to navigate between and arrange the windows.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] An area at the right side of the touch screen brings up a global context menu, and a similar strip at the left side brings up application-specific menus.
[src:kivy-framework/multi-touch] An open source community preview of the Con10uum window manager was made available in November, 2009.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] The API is cross-language and multi-platform.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] OpenGL ES is managed by the non-profit technology consortium Khronos Group.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] Vulkan, a next-generation API from Khronos, is made for simpler high performance drivers for mobile and desktop devices.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] Several versions of the OpenGL ES specification now exist.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] OpenGL ES 1.0 is drawn up against the OpenGL 1.3 specification, OpenGL ES 1.1 is defined relative to the OpenGL 1.5 specification and OpenGL ES 2.0 is defined relative to the OpenGL 2.0 specification.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] This means that, for example, an application written for OpenGL ES 1.0 should be easily portable to the desktop OpenGL 1.3; as the OpenGL ES is a stripped-down version of the API, the reverse may or may not be true, depending on the particular features used.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] OpenGL ES comes with its own version of shading language (OpenGL ES SL), which is different from OpenGL SL.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] Version 1.0 and 1.1 both have *common* (CM) and *common lite* (CL) profiles, the difference being that the *common lite* profile only supports fixed-point instead of floating point data type support, whereas *common* supports both.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] OpenGL ES 1.0 was released publicly July 28, 2003.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] OpenGL ES 1.0 is based on the original OpenGL 1.3 API, with much functionality removed and a little bit added.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] One significant difference between OpenGL and OpenGL ES is that OpenGL ES removed the need to bracket OpenGL library calls with `glBegin` and `glEnd`.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] Other significant differences are that the calling semantics for primitive rendering functions were changed in favor of vertex arrays, and fixed-point data types were introduced for vertex coordinates.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] Attributes were also added to better support the computational abilities of embedded processors, which often lack a floating point unit (FPU).
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] OpenGL ES 1.1 added features such as mandatory support for multitexture, better multitexture support (including combiners and dot product texture operations), automatic mipmap generation, vertex buffer objects, state queries, user clip planes, and greater control over point rendering.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] OpenGL ES 2.0 was publicly released in March 2007.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] It is roughly based on OpenGL 2.0, but it eliminates most of the fixed-function rendering pipeline in favor of a programmable one in a move similar to the transition from OpenGL 3.0 to 3.1.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] Control flow in shaders is generally limited to forward branching and to loops where the maximum number of iterations can easily be determined at compile time.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] Almost all rendering features of the transform and lighting stage, such as the specification of materials and light parameters formerly specified by the fixed-function API, are replaced by shaders written by the graphics programmer.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] As a result, OpenGL ES 2.0 is not backward compatible with OpenGL ES 1.1.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] Some incompatibilities between the desktop version of OpenGL and OpenGL ES 2.0 persisted until OpenGL 4.1, which added the `GL_ARB_ES2_compatibility` extension.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] The Khronos Group has written a document describing the differences between OpenGL ES 2.0 and ordinary OpenGL 2.0.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] The OpenGL ES 3.0 specification was publicly released in August 2012.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] It is backwards compatible with OpenGL ES 2.0, and partially compatible with WebGL 2.0, as WebGL 2.0 was designed to have a high degree of interoperability with OpenGL ES 3.0.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] The current version of the OpenGL ES 3.0 standard is 3.0.6, released in November 2019.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] The OpenGL ES 3.1 specification was publicly released in March 2014.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] OpenGL ES 3.1 is backward compatible with OpenGL ES 2.0 and 3.0, thus enabling applications to incrementally incorporate new features.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] The OpenGL ES 3.2 specification was publicly released in August 2015.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] Some more extensions are developed or in Development in Mesa for next OpenGL ES Version (see Mesamatrix).
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] OpenGL ES 1.0 added an official 3D graphics API to the Android and Symbian OS v8.0a operating systems, as well as by QNX It is also supported by the PlayStation 3 as one of its official graphics APIs (the other one being low level *libgcm* library) with Nvidia's Cg in lieu of GLSL.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] The PlayStation 3 also includes several features of the 2.0 version of OpenGL ES.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] Android Extension Pack (AEP) is a set of OpenGL ES 3.1 extensions, all bundled into a single extension introduced by Google in 2014.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] This allows applications to use all of the features of the set of extensions, while only testing for the presence of a single one.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] The AEP was officially added to Android Lollipop to provide extra features like tessellation over what was officially in the GLES 3.1 revision.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] OpenGL ES 3.2 update is largely made up of the AEP additions, which are already present in desktop OpenGL.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] OpenGL ES 3.2, incorporating the Android Extension Pack (AEP), "boasts a small number of improvements over last year’s OpenGL ES 3.1.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] Both make use of similar features from the AEP.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] OpenGL ES (and OpenGL) was deprecated in Apple's operating systems in favour of its own proprietary Metal graphics API, but still worked in up to at least iOS 12.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] There is currently no plan for a new core version of OpenGL ES, as adoption of Vulkan has been deemed to displace it in embedded and mobile applications.
[src:kivy-framework/opengl-es] Development of extensions to OpenGL ES continues as of 2017.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Guido van Rossum began working on Python in the late 1980s as a successor to the ABC programming language.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.0, released in 2008, was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Beginning with Python 3.5, capabilities and keywords for typing were added to the language, allowing optional static typing.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] As of 2026, the Python Software Foundation supports Python 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 3.14, following the project's annual release cycle and five-year support policy.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 is currently in the beta development phase, and the stable release is expected to launch in October 2026.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Earlier versions in the 3.x series have reached end-of-life and no longer receive security updates.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python has gained extensive use in the machine learning community.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] It is widely taught as an introductory programming language.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Since 2003, Python has consistently ranked among the top ten most popular programming languages in the TIOBE Programming Community Index, which ranks programming languages based on searches across 24 platforms.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python was conceived in the late 1980s by Guido van Rossum at Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] It was designed as a successor to the ABC programming language, which was inspired by SETL, capable of exception handling and interfacing with the Amoeba operating system.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python implementation began in December 1989.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Van Rossum first released it in 1991 as Python 0.9.0.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] In January 2019, active Python core developers elected a five-member Steering Council to lead the project.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] The name *Python* derives from the British comedy series *Monty Python's Flying Circus*.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python 2.0 was released on 16 October 2000, featuring many new features such as list comprehensions, cycle-detecting garbage collection, reference counting, and Unicode support.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python 2.7's end-of-life was initially set for 2015, and then postponed to 2020 out of concern that a large body of existing code could not easily be forward-ported to Python 3.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] It no longer receives security patches or updates.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] While Python 2.7 and older versions are officially unsupported, a different unofficial Python implementation, PyPy, continues to support Python 2, i.e., "2.7.18+" (plus 3.11), with the plus signifying (at least some) "backported security updates".
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.0 was released on 3 December 2008, and was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions, with some new semantics and changed syntax.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python 2.7.18, released in 2020, was the last release of Python 2.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Several releases in the Python 3.x series have added new syntax to the language, and made a few (considered very minor) backward-incompatible changes.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] As of May 2026, Python 3.14.6 is the latest stable release.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] All older 3.x versions had a security update down to Python 3.9.24 then again with 3.9.25, the final version in 3.9 series.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.10 is, since November 2025, the oldest supported branch.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 has an alpha released, and Android has an official downloadable executable available for Python 3.14.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Releases receive two years of full support followed by three years of security support.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python is a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Object-oriented programming and structured programming are fully supported, and many of their features support functional programming and aspect-oriented programming – including metaprogramming and metaobjects.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Many other paradigms are supported via extensions, including design by contract and logic programming.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python is often referred to as a *'glue language'* because it is purposely designed to be able to integrate components written in other languages.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python uses dynamic typing and a combination of reference counting and a cycle-detecting garbage collector for memory management.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] It uses dynamic name resolution (late binding), which binds method and variable names during program execution.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python's design offers some support for functional programming in the "Lisp tradition".
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] It has `filter`, `map`, and `reduce` functions; list comprehensions, dictionaries, sets, and generator expressions.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] The standard library has two modules (`itertools` and `functools`) that implement functional tools borrowed from Haskell and Standard ML.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] However, Python has received criticism for violating these principles and adding unnecessary language bloat.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Responses to these criticisms note that the Zen of Python is a guideline rather than a rule.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] The addition of some new features had been controversial: Guido van Rossum resigned as *Benevolent Dictator for Life* after conflict about adding the assignment expression operator in Python 3.8.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Nevertheless, rather than building all functionality into its core, Python was designed to be highly extensible through modules.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] This compact modularity has made it particularly popular as a means of adding programmable interfaces to existing applications.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Van Rossum's vision of a small core language with a large standard library and an easily extensible interpreter stemmed from his frustrations with ABC, which represented the opposite approach.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python claims to strive for a simpler, less-cluttered syntax and grammar, while giving developers a choice in their coding methodology.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python lacks `do .. while` loops, which Rossum considered harmful.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] In contrast to Perl's motto "there is more than one way to do it", Python advocates an approach where "there should be one – and preferably only one – obvious way to do it".
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] In practice, however, Python provides many ways to achieve a given goal.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] There are at least three ways to format a string literal, with no certainty as to which one a programmer should use.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python's developers typically prioritize readability over performance.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] For example, they reject patches to non-critical parts of the CPython reference implementation that would offer increases in speed that do not justify the cost of clarity and readability.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Execution speed can be improved by moving speed-critical functions to extension modules written in languages such as C, or by using a just-in-time compiler like PyPy.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Also, it is possible to transpile to other languages.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] However, this approach either fails to achieve the expected speed-up, since Python is a very dynamic language, or only a restricted subset of Python is compiled (with potential minor semantic changes).
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be a fun language to use.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] This goal is reflected in the name – a tribute to the British comedy group Monty Python – and in playful approaches to some tutorials and reference materials.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] For instance, some code examples use the terms "spam" and "eggs" (in reference to a Monty Python sketch), rather than the typical terms "foo" and "bar".
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] A common neologism in the Python community is *pythonic*, which has a broad range of meanings related to program style: Pythonic code may use Python idioms well; be natural or show fluency in the language; or conform with Python's minimalist philosophy and emphasis on readability.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] There are 3 kinds of PEPs, with those are being *standards track PEP*, *Informational PEP* and *Process PEP*s which has their own unique meanings.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] They were firstly introduced in 2000, inspired by other RfCs (requests for comments) and Desing Enhancement Proposals.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Most known PEPs are PEP – 1, PEP – 8, PEP – 20, PEP – 257 and others.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be an easily readable language.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Its formatting is visually uncluttered and often uses English keywords where other languages use punctuation.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Unlike many other languages, it does not use curly brackets to delimit blocks, and semicolons after statements are allowed but rarely used.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] It has fewer syntactic exceptions and special cases than C or Pascal.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python uses whitespace indentation, rather than curly brackets or keywords, to delimit blocks.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] An increase in indentation comes after certain statements; a decrease in indentation signifies the end of the current block.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Thus, the program's visual structure accurately represents its semantic structure.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] This feature is sometimes termed the off-side rule.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Some other languages use indentation this way; but in most, indentation has no semantic meaning.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] The recommended indent size is four spaces.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] The assignment statement (`=`) binds a name as a reference to a separate, dynamically allocated object.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Variables may subsequently be rebound at any time to any object.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] In Python, a variable name is a generic reference holder without a fixed data type; however, it always refers to *some* object with a type.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] This is called dynamic typing—in contrast to statically-typed languages, where each variable may contain only a value of a certain type.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python does not support tail call optimization or first-class continuations; according to Van Rossum, the language never will.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] However, better support for coroutine-like functionality is provided by extending Python's generators.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Before 2.5, generators were lazy iterators; data was passed unidirectionally out of the generator.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] From Python 2.5 on, it is possible to pass data back into a generator function; and from version 3.3, data can be passed through multiple stack levels.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] In Python, a distinction between expressions and statements is rigidly enforced, in contrast to languages such as Common Lisp, Scheme, or Ruby.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] A statement cannot be part of an expression; because of this restriction, expressions such as list and `dict` comprehensions (and lambda expressions) cannot contain statements.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] As a particular case, an assignment statement such as `a = 1` cannot be part of the conditional expression of a conditional statement.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python uses duck typing, and it has typed objects but untyped variable names.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Type constraints are not checked at definition time; rather, operations on an object may fail at usage time, indicating that the object is not of an appropriate type.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Despite being dynamically typed, Python is strongly typed, forbidding operations that are poorly defined (e.g., adding a number and a string) rather than quietly attempting to interpret them.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python allows programmers to define their own types using classes, most often for object-oriented programming.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] New instances of classes are constructed by calling the class, for example, `SpamClass()` or `EggsClass()`); the classes are instances of the metaclass `type` (which is an instance of itself), thereby allowing metaprogramming and reflection.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Before version 3.0, Python had two kinds of classes, both using the same syntax: *old-style* and *new-style*.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Current Python versions support the semantics of only the new style.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python supports optional type annotations.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] These annotations are not enforced by the language, but may be used by external tools such as **mypy** to catch errors.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python includes a module `typing` including several type names for type annotations.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Also, mypy supports a Python compiler called mypyc, which leverages type annotations for optimization.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python includes conventional symbols for arithmetic operators (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`), the floor-division operator `//`, and the modulo operator `%`.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] (With the modulo operator, a remainder can be negative, e.g., `4 % -3 == -2`.) Python also offers the `**` symbol for exponentiation, e.g.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] These operators work as in traditional mathematics; with the same precedence rules, the infix operators `+` and `-` can also be unary, to represent positive and negative numbers respectively.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Division between integers produces floating-point results.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] In Python terms, the `/` operator represents *true division* (or simply *division*), while the `//` operator represents *floor division.* Before version 3.0, the `/` operator represents *classic division*.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Rounding towards negative infinity, though a different method than in most languages, adds consistency to Python.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] For instance, this rounding implies that the equation `(a + b)//b == a//b + 1` is always true.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Also, the rounding implies that the equation `b*(a//b) + a%b == a` is valid for both positive and negative values of `a`.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] As expected, the result of `a%b` lies in the half-open interval [0, *b*), where `b` is a positive integer; however, maintaining the validity of the equation requires that the result must lie in the interval (*b*, 0] when `b` is negative.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python provides a `round` function for rounding a float to the nearest integer.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] For tie-breaking, Python 3 uses the *round to even* method: `round(1.5)` and `round(2.5)` both produce `2`.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python allows Boolean expressions that contain multiple equality relations to be consistent with general usage in mathematics.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] For example, the expression `a < b < c` tests whether `a` is less than `b` and `b` is less than `c`.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] C-derived languages interpret this expression differently: in C, the expression would first evaluate `a < b`, resulting in 0 or 1, and that result would then be compared with `c`.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python uses arbitrary-precision arithmetic for all integer operations.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] The `Decimal` type/class in the `decimal` module provides decimal floating-point numbers to a pre-defined arbitrary precision with several rounding modes.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] The `Fraction` class in the `fractions` module provides arbitrary precision for rational numbers.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Due to Python's extensive mathematics library and the third-party library NumPy, the language is frequently used for scientific scripting in tasks such as numerical data processing and manipulation.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Functions are created in Python by using the `def` keyword.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] A function is defined similarly to how it is called, by first providing the function name and then the required parameters.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] To assign a default value to a function parameter in case no actual value is provided at run time, variable-definition syntax can be used inside the function header.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python's large standard library is commonly cited as one of its greatest strengths.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] For Internet-facing applications, many standard formats and protocols such as MIME and HTTP are supported.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] The language includes modules for creating graphical user interfaces, connecting to relational databases, generating pseudorandom numbers, arithmetic with arbitrary-precision decimals, manipulating regular expressions, and unit testing.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Some parts of the standard library are covered by specifications—for example, the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI) implementation `wsgiref` follows PEP 333—but most parts are specified by their code, internal documentation, and test suites.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] However, because most of the standard library is cross-platform Python code, only a few modules must be altered or rewritten for variant implementations.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] As of 13 March 2025, the Python Package Index (PyPI), the official repository for third-party Python software, contains over 614,339 packages.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Most Python implementations (including CPython) include a read–eval–print loop (REPL); this permits the environment to function as a command line interpreter, with which users enter statements sequentially and receive results immediately.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Also, CPython is bundled with an integrated development environment (IDE) called IDLE, which is oriented toward beginners.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Other shells, including IDLE and IPython, add additional capabilities such as improved auto-completion, session-state retention, and syntax highlighting.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] CPython is the reference implementation of Python.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] This implementation is written in C, meeting the C11 standard since version 3.11.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Older versions use the C89 standard with several select C99 features, but third-party extensions are not limited to older C versions—e.g., they can be implemented using C11 or C++.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] CPython compiles Python programs into an intermediate bytecode, which is then executed by a virtual machine.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] CPython is distributed with a large standard library written in a combination of C and native Python.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] CPython is available for many platforms, including Windows and most modern Unix-like systems, including macOS (and Apple M1 Macs, since Python 3.9.1, using an experimental installer).
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Starting with Python 3.9, the Python installer intentionally fails to install on Windows 7 and 8; Windows XP was supported until Python 3.5.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Old Python versions unofficially support VMS (mostly supporting) and OpenVMS x86-64 has Python 3.10 support.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Platform portability was one of Python's earliest priorities.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] During development of Python 1 and 2, even OS/2 and Solaris were supported; since that time, support has been dropped for many platforms.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] All current Python versions (since 3.7) support only operating systems that feature multithreading, by now supporting not nearly as many operating systems (dropping many outdated) than in the past.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] All alternative implementations have at least slightly different semantics.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] For example, an alternative may include unordered dictionaries, in contrast to other current Python versions.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] As another example in the larger Python ecosystem, PyPy does not support the full C Python API.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Creating an executable with Python often is done by bundling an entire Python interpreter into the executable, which causes binary sizes to be massive for small programs, yet there exist implementations that are capable of truly compiling Python.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Stackless Python is a significant fork of CPython that implements microthreads.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] This implementation uses the call stack differently, thus allowing massively concurrent programs.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] A performance comparison among various Python implementations, using a non-numerical (combinatorial) workload, was presented at EuroSciPy '13.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] In addition, Python's performance relative to other programming languages is benchmarked by The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] There are several approaches to optimizing Python performance, despite the inherent slowness of an interpreted language.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python's development is conducted mostly through the *Python Enhancement Proposal* (PEP) process; this process is the primary mechanism for proposing major new features, collecting community input on issues, and documenting Python design decisions.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python coding style is covered in PEP 8.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Outstanding PEPs are reviewed and commented on by the Python community and the steering council.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Enhancement of the language corresponds with development of the CPython reference implementation.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] The mailing list python-dev is the primary forum for the language's development.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Specific issues were originally discussed in the Roundup bug tracker hosted by the foundation.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] In 2022, all issues and discussions were migrated to GitHub.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Development originally took place on a self-hosted source-code repository running Mercurial, until Python moved to GitHub in January 2017.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Many alpha, beta, and release-candidates are also released as previews and for testing before final releases.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Although there is a rough schedule for releases, they are often delayed if the code is not ready yet.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python's development team monitors the state of the code by running a large unit test suite during development.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] The major academic conference on Python is PyCon.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Also, there are special Python mentoring programs, such as PyLadies.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python's name is inspired by the British comedy group Monty Python, whom Python creator Guido van Rossum enjoyed while developing the language.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Monty Python references appear frequently in Python code and culture; for example, the metasyntactic variables often used in Python literature are *spam* and *eggs*, rather than the traditional *foo* and *bar*.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Also, the official Python documentation contains various references to Monty Python routines.
[src:kivy-framework/python-programming-language] Python users are sometimes referred to as "Pythonistas".
